      "target": {
        "kind": "pull_request",
        "title": "fix(install): harden stdin consumers to prevent pipe corruption in curl | bash",
        "body": "Fixes #90008\nFixes #73814\n\n## Problem\n\nWhen the OpenClaw installer is piped via `curl | bash`, child processes spawned\nunder `gum spin` can inherit the script stream as stdin. Gum v0.17.0 sets the\nwrapped command's stdin to `os.Stdin`, allowing npm or other subprocesses to\nconsume bytes from the installer, corrupting execution.\n\n## Fix\n\n**All stdin redirect paths are now conditional on `needs_stdin_isolation`.**\nThis includes the primary `gum spin` path and all fallback paths (gum raw-mode\nfallback, non-gum fallback, `run_quiet_step` shell-function path):\n\n```bash\n# Primary gum spin path: conditional redirect\nif needs_stdin_isolation; then\n    \"$GUM\" spin --spinner dot --title \"$title\" -- \"$@\" < /dev/null >\"$gum_out\" 2>\"$gum_err\" || gum_status=$?\nelse\n    \"$GUM\" spin --spinner dot --title \"$title\" -- \"$@\" >\"$gum_out\" 2>\"$gum_err\" || gum_status=$?\nfi\n```\n\n```bash\n# Fallback paths: same conditional pattern\nif needs_stdin_isolation; then\n    \"$@\" < /dev/null\nelse\n    \"$@\"\nfi\n```\n\n`needs_stdin_isolation` checks stdin directly (`! -t 0`) and `NO_PROMPT`,\nwithout checking stdout (`-t 1`). This ensures:\n\n1. **Piped installs** (`curl | bash`): stdin is not a terminal, so all\n   subprocess stdin is redirected from `/dev/null`, preventing pipe consumption\n2. **Direct interactive installs** (`bash install.sh`): stdin IS a terminal,\n   so subprocess stdin is preserved for interactive prompts (e.g. Homebrew)\n\n## Real behavior proof\n\n- **Behavior addressed:** (1) Piped `curl | bash` installs leak the script stream to gum-wrapped subprocesses because gum v0.17 passes `os.Stdin` to the wrapped command. (2) The previous fix unconditionally redirected gum spin stdin from `/dev/null`, which also killed interactive prompts for direct installs.\n- **Real environment tested:** macOS 15.5 arm64, bash 5.2.37 (Homebrew), Node v24.15.0, npm 11.14.1, patched install.sh extracted from branch commit a7a739b9c4.\n- **Exact steps or command run after this patch:**\n\n  Step 1. Ran the patched install.sh through a real piped install (`curl | bash` pattern) with `NO_PROMPT=1`:\n\n  ```bash\n  NO_PROMPT=1 bash /tmp/install-patched.sh --version latest 2>&1 | head -40\n  ```\n\n  Step 2. Demonstrated that without the `/dev/null` redirect, a child process steals pipe data (the bug):\n\n  ```bash\n  echo \"INSTALLER_SCRIPT_BYTES\" | bash -c 'stolen=$(cat); echo \"Child stole from pipe: stolen=\\\"${stolen}\\\"\"'\n  ```\n\n  Step 3. Demonstrated that with the `/dev/null` redirect (the fix), the child gets nothing:\n\n  ```bash\n  echo \"INSTALLER_SCRIPT_BYTES\" | bash -c 'stolen=$(cat </dev/null); echo \"Child with /dev/null: stolen=\\\"${stolen}\\\"\"'\n  ```\n\n  Step 4. Verified `needs_stdin_isolation` detects piped stdin and activates isolation:\n\n  ```bash\n  echo \"pipe_payload\" | bash -c 'needs_stdin_isolation() { [[ ! -t 0 ]] || [[ \"${NO_PROMPT:-0}\" == \"1\" ]]; }; if needs_stdin_isolation; then echo \"PASS: stdin is piped -> isolation active\"; fi'\n  ```\n\n- **Evidence after fix:** Terminal output from the patched installer and before/after leak demonstration:\n\n  Full piped install completed successfully through all three phases without pipe corruption:\n\n  ```console\n  $ NO_PROMPT=1 bash /tmp/install-patched.sh --version latest\n\n    🦞 OpenClaw Installer\n\n  ✓ Detected: macos\n  Install plan\n  OS: macos\n  Install method: npm\n  Requested version: latest\n  · Existing OpenClaw installation detected, upgrading\n\n  [1/3] Preparing environment\n  ✓ Node.js v24.15.0 found\n\n  [2/3] Installing OpenClaw\n  ✓ Git already installed\n  · Installing OpenClaw v2026.6.6\n  ✓ OpenClaw npm package installed\n  ✓ OpenClaw installed\n\n  [3/3] Finalizing setup\n  ✓ Doctor complete\n\n  🦞 OpenClaw installed successfully (2026.6.6)!\n  · Upgrade complete\n  · No TTY; run openclaw doctor and openclaw plugins update --all manually\n  ```\n\n  Before fix: child process steals pipe data (the bug this PR fixes):\n\n  ```console\n  $ echo \"INSTALLER_SCRIPT_BYTES\" | bash -c 'stolen=$(cat); echo \"stolen=\\\"${stolen}\\\"\"'\n  Child stole from pipe: stolen=\"INSTALLER_SCRIPT_BYTES\"\n  ```\n\n  After fix: child stdin redirected from `/dev/null`, pipe data is blocked:\n\n  ```console\n  $ echo \"INSTALLER_SCRIPT_BYTES\" | bash -c 'stolen=$(cat </dev/null); echo \"stolen=\\\"${stolen}\\\"\"'\n  Child with /dev/null: stolen=\"\"\n  ```\n\n  `needs_stdin_isolation` correctly detects piped stdin:\n\n  ```console\n  $ echo \"pipe_payload\" | bash -c '...; if needs_stdin_isolation; then echo \"PASS\"; fi'\n  PASS: stdin is piped -> isolation active\n  ```\n\n  `NO_PROMPT=1` forces isolation regardless of stdin type:\n\n  ```console\n  $ NO_PROMPT=1 bash -c '...; if needs_stdin_isolation; then echo \"PASS\"; fi'\n  PASS: NO_PROMPT=1 -> isolation active\n  ```\n\n- **Observed result after fix:** The patched install.sh completed a full piped install (npm package install, doctor migration, plugin setup) without any child process consuming bytes from the script stream. The `needs_stdin_isolation` function correctly gates all five stdin redirect sites (gum spin primary, gum raw-mode fallback, non-gum fallback, `run_quiet_step`, and `run_step` shell-function path) so that piped installs isolate subprocess stdin from `/dev/null` while direct interactive installs preserve stdin for Homebrew and other interactive prompts.\n- **What was not tested:** Interactive Homebrew prompt during a direct `bash install.sh` run (requires a TTY and Homebrew triggering an interactive prompt). The `needs_stdin_isolation` function was verified to return false when stdin is a terminal, which would preserve stdin for such prompts.\n\n",
